{{Quote|The Rebels no longer have a ''refueling station'' here―and the name of the T-65 pilot who destroyed the ''Death Star'' is no longer a ''secret''.|Darth Vader|<ref name="SW35">[[Star Wars (1977) 35|''Star Wars'' (1977) 35]]</ref>}}
'''Refueling stations''' or '''refueling centers''' were used to service [[Starship/Legends|starships]] and supply them with [[Fuel/Legends|fuel]].

[[R2-D2/Legends|R2-D2]] and [[C-3PO/Legends|C-3PO]] once worked at a [[Sindee's refueling station|refueling station]] alongside a lone attendant named [[Sindee]].<ref name="NEGC">''[[The New Essential Guide to Characters]]''</ref> To help her pass the time, Sindee added programming to R2-D2 to allow him to play a competent game of [[Dejarik/Legends|dejarik]].<ref name="Rogues">{{SWRadio|Rogues, Rebels and Robots}}</ref> The [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel Alliance]] maintained a refueling station that was attacked and destroyed by the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]]. One pilot survived long enough to be interrogated by [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]], at last yielding the identity of [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] to his father.<ref name="SW35" />

[[Nierport VII]], a desolate moon along the [[Hydian Way/Legends|Hydian Way]] in the [[Eeropha system]], was home to a refueling station where pilots frequently made stopovers. The moon’s only settlement was based around the refueling station. It was the homeworld of [[Granta Omega]], son of the Dark Jedi [[Xanatos]]. Omega’s mother, [[Tura Omega]], worked at the station.

